A096904.name: A card-arranging problem: number of permutations p_1, ..., p_n of 1, ..., n such that i + p_i is a cube for every i.
formula: a(n) = permanent(m), where the n X n matrix m is defined by m(i,j) = 1 or 0, depending on whether i+j is a cube or not.

A096905.name: A card-arranging problem: values of n such that there exists a permutation p_1, ..., p_n of 1, ..., n such that i + p_i is a fourth power for every i.

A096906.name: A card-arranging problem: values of n such that there exists a permutation p_1, ..., p_n of 1, ..., n such that i + p_i is a fifth power for every i.

A096907.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives a values.

A096908.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives b values.

A096909.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives c values.

A096910.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives d values.

A096911.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts with exactly one even part.
formula: G.f.: x^2/(1-x^2)*Product(1+x^(2*i+1), i=0..infinity). More generally, g.f. for number of partitions of n into distinct parts with exactly k even parts is x^(k*(k+1))/Product(1-x^(2*i), i=1..k)*Product(1+x^(2*i+1), i=0..infinity).
a(n) ~ 3^(1/4) * exp(Pi*sqrt(n/6)) / (2^(5/4) * Pi * n^(1/4)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 29 2018

A096912.name: Numbers n such that 111*10^n+1 is prime.

A096913.name: Numbers n such that (largest digit of n)^(smallest digit of n) + n is a square.

A096914.name: Number of partitions of 2*n into distinct parts with exactly two odd parts.
formula: G.f. for number of partitions of n into distinct parts with exactly k odd parts is x^(k^2)*Product(1+x^(2*m), m=1..infinity)/Product(1-x^(2*m), m=1..k).

A096915.name: Smallest prime which when appended to n produces a prime.

A096916.name: Lesser prime factor of n-th product of two distinct primes.

A096917.name: Smallest prime factor of n-th product of 3 distinct primes.

A096918.name: Intermediate prime factor of n-th product of 3 distinct primes.

A096919.name: Greatest prime factor of n-th product of 3 distinct primes.

A096920.name: Expansion of q^(-1/12) * eta(q^2)^4 / (eta(q)^2 * eta(q^4)) in powers of q.
formula: G.f.: Product_{k>0} (1 - x^(4*k)) * (1 + x^(2*k-1))^2. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 25 2008

Expansion of psi(q) * chi(q) = f(q) / chi(-q) = f(q)^2 / phi(-q^2) = phi(-q^2) / chi(-q)^2 = phi(q) / chi(-q^2) = psi(q)^2 / f(-q^4) = f(-q^4) * chi(q)^2 where phi(), psi(), chi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Euler transform of period 4 sequence [ 2, -2, 2, -1, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 25 2008
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (576 t)) = 12^(1/2) (t/i)^(1/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is g.f. for A138559.

A096922.name: Numbers n for which there is a unique k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096923.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly two k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096924.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly three k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096925.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly four k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096926.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly five k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096927.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly six k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096928.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly seven k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096929.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly eight k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096930.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly nine k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096931.name: Numbers n for which there are exactly ten k such that n = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096932.name: Smallest number having exactly s divisors, where s is the n-th semiprime (A001358).

A096935.name: Smallest number k such that in its decimal representation the first n digits of Pi=3.14... are contained in 11^k.

A096936.name: Half of number of integer solutions to the equation x^2 + 3y^2 = n.
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 3*(1+(-1)^e)/2, a(3^e) = 1, a(p^e) = (1+(-1)^e)/2 if p==2 (mod 3) and a(p^e) = 1+e if p==1 (mod 3). - Corrected by _Antti Karttunen_, Nov 20 2017

A096937.name: Least k such that k*P(n)#/2 - 2 and k*P(n)#/2 + 2 are both primes, where P(i)= i-th prime, P(i)# = i-th primorial.

A096938.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 60F for the Monster group.
formula: Euler transform of period 10 sequence [1, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, ...]. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 19 2004
Expansion of q^(1/6)eta(q^2)eta(q^5)/(eta(q)eta(q^10)) in powers of q.
Given g.f. A(x), then B(x)=(A(x^6)/x)^2 satisfies 0=f(B(x), B(x^2)) where f(u, v)=(u^3+v^3)(1+uv)-uv(1-uv)^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 18 2005
G.f.: 1/product_{k>=1} (1-x^k+x^(2*k)-x^(3*k)+x^(4*k)) = 1/Product_{k>0} P10(x^k) where P10 is the 10th cyclotomic polynomial.
a(n) ~ exp(2*Pi*sqrt(n/15)) / (2 * 15^(1/4) * n^(3/4)) * (1 - (3*sqrt(15)/(16*Pi) + Pi/(6*sqrt(15))) / sqrt(n)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 31 2015, extended Jan 21 2017

A096939.name: Number of sets of odd number of even lists, cf. A000262.

A096940.name: Pascal (1,5) triangle.
formula: Recursion: a(n, m)=0 if m>n, a(0, 0)= 5; a(n, 0)=1 if n>=1; a(n, m) = a(n-1, m) + a(n-1, m-1).
G.f. column m (without leading zeros): (5-4*x)/(1-x)^(m+1), m>=0.

A096942.name: Fifth column of (1,5)-Pascal triangle A096940.
formula: a(n) = sum_{k=1..n} (sum_{i=1..k) i*(n-k+5)). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 26 2013

A096948.name: Triangular table read by rows: T(n,m) = number of rectangles found in an n X m rectangle built from 1 X 1 squares, 1 <= m <= n.
formula: T(n, m) = t(n)*t(m) if n>=m else 0, with the triangular numbers t(n):= A000217(n), n>=1.
G.f. for column m (without leading zeros): t(m)*(x/(1-x)^3 - sum(t(k)*x^k, k=0..m-1)/x^m, m>=1.

A096949.name: Numerators of partial sums of series for 3*arctanh(1/3) = (3/2)*log(2).
formula: a(n)=numerator(A(n)) with the rational number A(n):= sum(((1/3)^(2*k))/(2*k+1), k=0..n) in lowest terms.

A096950.name: Denominators of partial sums of series for 3*arctanh(1/3) = (3/2)*log(2).
formula: a(n)=denominator(A(n)) with the rational number A(n):= sum(((1/3)^(2*k))/(2*k+1), k=0..n) in lowest terms.

A096951.name: Sum of odd powers of 2 and of 3 divided by 5.

A096952.name: Numerators of upper bounds for Lagrange remainder in Taylor's expansion of log((1+x)/(1-x)) for x=1/3, multiplied by 6/5.

A096953.name: Denominators of upper bounds for Lagrange-remainder in Taylor's expansion of log((1+x)/(1-x)) multiplied by 6/5.

A096954.name: From Machin's formula: rational approximation for Pi/4=.78539816339744830962...
formula: a(n)=numerator(M(n)), with M(n)=4*arctan(1/5, n) - arctan(1/239, n) with arctan(x, n):=sum((((-1)^k)*x^(2k+1))/(2*k+1), k=0..n).

A096955.name: From Machin's formula: rational approximation for Pi/4 = 0.78539816339744... = A003881.
formula: a(n) = denominator(M(n)), with M(n)=4*arctan(1/5, n) - arctan(1/239, n) with arctan(x, n):=sum((((-1)^k)*x^(2k+1))/(2*k+1), k=0..n).

A096956.name: Pascal (1,6) triangle.
formula: Recursion: a(n,m)=0 if m > n, a(0,0) = 6; a(n,0) = 1 if n >= 1; a(n,m) = a(n-1, m) + a(n-1, m-1).
G.f. column m (without leading zeros): (6-5*x)/(1-x)^(m+1), m >= 0.

A096957.name: Fourth column (m=3) of (1,6)-Pascal triangle A096956.
formula: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 6*a(n-2) + 4*a(n-3) - a(n-4) for n>3. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Apr 19 2017

A096958.name: Fifth column (m=4) of (1,6)-Pascal triangle A096956.
formula: a(n) = sum_{k=1..n+1} ( sum_{i=1..k} i*(n-k+7) ). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 26 2013

A096961.name: Sum_{0<d|n, n/d odd} d^7.
formula: Expansion of (E_8(q) - E_8(q^2)) / 480 in powers of q where E_8() is an Eisenstein series (A008410). - _Michael Somos_, Jan 09 2015

A096965.name: Number of sets of even number of even lists, cf. A000262.

A096966.name: Triangle (read by rows) in which the number of entries in a row only increases by 1 every other row, the first column and the 'diagonal' is set to all 1's and a(i,j) = a(i-1,j) + a(i-1,j-1) + a(i-2,j-1) + a(i-3,j-1) for other entries.

A096969.name: Number of ways to number the cells of an n X n square grid with 1,2,3,...,n^2 so that successive integers are in adjacent cells (horizontally or vertically).

A096970.name: Number of ways to number the cells of an n X n square grid with 1,2,3,...,n^2 so that successive integers are in the same row or column.

A096971.name: G.f. satisfies: A(x) = A( x^2*A000108(x^2) )*x*A000984(x^2), where A000108(x) is the g.f. for the Catalan sequence and A000984(x) = d/dx x*A000108(x).

A096972.name: Number of preimages of n (or immediate predecessors) under map f(k) = k + (product of nonzero digits of k).

A096974.name: Numbers n such that A096123(n) = n!/(nextprime(n/2)-1)!.

A096975.name: Trace sequence of a path graph plus loop.

A096976.name: Number of walks of length n on P_3 plus a loop at the end.

A096978.name: Sum of the areas of the first n Jacobsthal rectangles.

A096979.name: Sum of the areas of the first n+1 Pell triangles.

A096980.name: Expansion of (1+3x)/(1-2x-7x^2).
formula: a(n) = 3*Sum_{k=0..floor((n-1)/2)} binomial(n-k-1, k)*(7/2)^k*2^(n-k-1) + Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k, k)*(7/2)^k*2^(n-k).
Satisfies recurrence relation system a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 2*b(n-1), b(n) = 2*a(n-1) - b(n-1), a(0)=1, b(0)=1. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 11 2017

A096981.name: Number of partitions of n into parts congruent to {0, 1, 3, 5} mod 6.
formula: Expansion of q^(5/24) * eta(q^2) / (eta(q) * eta(q^6)) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 08 2012
Euler transform of period 6 sequence [1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 1, ...]. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Aug 20 2004

A096982.name: Define a(1)=0. Then define b(1)=1, b(2)=1 and for k > 2, b(k) = (b(k-2) + b(k-1)) (mod n). This gives for each n a cyclic repetitive sequence; a(n) is the least k > 1 for the first 1 of the sequence 1,1,....

A096983.name: a(n) is the smallest prime whose base-n digits add up to a composite number.

A096984.name: Another version of A005512, which is the main entry for this sequence.

A096985.name: Numbers n such that n*n! - NextPrime[n] is prime.

A096986.name: Numbers n such that n*n! + (smallest prime > n) is prime.

A096988.name: Initial values for f(x)=sigma(phi(x))=A062402(x) such that iteration of f ends in cycle of length=1.

A096989.name: Initial values for f(x)=sigma(phi[x])=A062402[x] such that iteration of f ends in cycle of length=2.

A096990.name: Initial values for f(x)=sigma(phi(x))=A062402(x) such that iteration of f ends in cycle of length=3.

A096991.name: Initial values for f(x)=sigma(phi[x])=A062402[x] such that iteration of f ends in cycle of length=4.

A096992.name: Initial values for f(x)=sigma(phi[x])=A062402[x] such that iteration of f ends in cycle of length=6.

A096993.name: Function A062402(x) = sigma(phi(x)) is iterated with initial value=n. a(n) is the length of cycle into which the trajectory merges.

A096994.name: Number of transient terms if f(x)=phi(sigma(x))=A062401 is iterated at initial value 2^n. Equilibrium terms are listed in A096852.

A096995.name: Number of transient terms if f(x) = sigma(phi(x)) = A062402 is iterated at initial value = 2^n.

A096996.name: a(n) is the smallest initial value if function f(x)=sigma(phi(x))=A062402(x) is iterated and the iteration ends in a cycle of length n.

A096997.name: If f(x)=sigma(phi[x])=A062402[x] function is iterated starting from these listed values, then the start-value never returns. These are the transient terms of this iteration. Never occur in terminal cycles.

A096998.name: Consider iteration of the function f(x)=sigma(phi(x))=A062402(x). Sequence gives numbers n such that the trajectory of n returns to n.

A096999.name: A062401(x)=phi[sigma(x)] function is iterated; initial value=2^n; a(n)=largest term of trajectory.

A097000.name: A062401(x)=phi[sigma(x)] function is iterated; initial value=2^n; a(n)=smallest term of trajectory.
